description: Set by Adam Jorna, H00. A competition problem from IBC2000 forms the start of Iffley's easiest circuit. Finishing on 96 is a more satisfying alternative.

index: Buzz, Buzz goes the Honey Bee

description: First ascent by Christian, T01. Something of a one-move-wonder, but still worthwhile. Either use your left foot in the slot, or heel-hook the arête for a brave final move.
First ascent by Gillian, H02. A clever move through hold 42 will put you in a good position for an unlikely-looking finish. Tricky for the grade…
Set by Alison Parker, M02. A worthwhile amusement for those without long reach.
Set by Adam Jorna, H00. A competition problem from IBC2000 , which provided surprising difficulties. Although not particularly reachy, the short may struggle with the step up to 40B.
Set by Paul & Christian, H01. A tricky move through 42 needs some clever positioning, good body tension, and perhaps a chip for the left foot...

Set by Andy and Tim for the Hilary 2003 compeition. Brilliant technical moves up the left-hand arête. Several possibilities exist, making this problem an ideal project for those wishing to push their grade in to the '5 somethings'. This problem is usually peoples' first real experience of smearing on smooth paint... (It does work!)
Set by Seshadri Nadathur, first ascent by Steve Broadbent, M06. A pleasant rising traverse with an interesting Gaston move to finish.

index: Of Ruine and Some Blazing Starre
The Art of the Hand Jam

description: Set by Geoff Hannis for the 2007 competition whilst he was in America…! The initial moves require more skill than just a long stretch right to 43…

Set by Nick Brown for the 2006 competition. A lovely move up the arête is followed by a frustrating slap to a tiny crimp, where failure is almost a certainty! Grab it, hold it, and count to five to prove that gravity really hasn't noticed you. The name is a clue to the outcome, albeit subtle.

index: Step on my Old Size Nines
description: First ascent by Philip Frampton, T01. The sit start is only 5a for those who can reach 40A from the ground (you see a lot of people sitting on mats here!)
Set by Geoff Hannis for the 2007 competition. The sit start gives many people difficulties, but things ease considerably above.
First ascent by Adrian Baugh, T00. Probably deserves more attention than it currently attracts, featuring nice moves on pinches and side-pulls.
Set by Steve Broadbent for the 2007 competition. Brilliant steep bouldering that is considerably easier than it looks. Standing up on 40A requires nothing more than belief that it's easy…

index: Insert Tab A into Slot B

description: One of the original numbered problems, set by Tim Woolllings M99. Nice moves but with an odd, reachy finish…

index: The Rise and Fall of the Roman Empire
The Hand that Rocks the Cradle
description: Set by Geoff Hannis for the 2007 competition. Initial technical moves lead to a brilliant, powerful finish.

index: Sunflowers are the way Forward in Life!
Strong Like a Left Handed Bull
Smart Like Tractor / There was no Ice Cube

description: First ascent by Adrian Baugh, M99. An unpleasant and awkward problem. Jan, elevator, or fail!
A nice beginning to Hebrews 10.9, posted in M01 and requiring either a bit of a reach or a fun little pop to 64. Believe it or not, the name confusion comes from someone's very bad handwriting!

index: The Very Big and the Very Big
The Adventure of the Dancing Men

description: First ascent by Dave Hofer, H00, with the sit start added by Adrian Baugh. Good climbing, but the shorter people soon get their own revenge with the variation "Tall Man Rides a Shovelhead".
First ascent by Steve Broadbent, 2012. Tricky arete-based antics from the 2012 competition.

index: Let's Twist Again (Like we did last Fall)
Judean People's Front Crack Suicide Squad

description: A classic, set by Martyn Beardsley H01, first ascent by Steve Broadbent. The original 6a grade overstates the problem's difficulty if the feet are used correctly. The name was a response to Adrian's PARA, but this time the 'C' doesn't stand for Californian!

index: Once Upon a time in Devon

description: First ascent by Paul Cooper, H01. The culmination of attempts to find a problem that the "medium height people" couldn't do! If you're tall it's easy (4c) but if you can't reach across to 98 then the problem takes on a whole new level of interest.
A rarely climbed traverse, posted by Zorro.

index: Till her Daddy Takes her T-bird Away!
The Wicked Witch of the West

description: First ascent by Katja Broadbent, M06. This excellent variation on "The Bad Touch" features the same technical moves as the original, but can be climbed  by shorter climbers who may not be able to reach 62B. After a strenuous sit-start, strong fingers and good body-positioning are rquired for the brilliant upper moves.
Set by Steve & Huw, M00. A fine line, hard at the grade, with superbly delicate climbing requiring finger strength and balance. One of the calssic problems from a goldern era of Iffley bouldering.

index: The Leap of the Long Sheep

description: First ascent by Matt Titterington, H15. A powerful pinch in 93 will help. Eliminating 93 gives the much more challenging "Dawes Rides a Tiger" (B4 6a), fa. Mike Pearson H15.

index: The Spark that set the Flame
description: First ascent by Huw Jenkins, H01. A variation on Adrian's Spark of Obsession. 41A is undercut only.

First climbed by Adrian Baugh, H01. After a crucial chip broke on the arête this problem became slightly harder., but has been repeated dynamically by Geoff Hannis at 6a. Named after a quote in the Moonlight Tandoori by a certain well known climber…

index: The Very Small and the Very Small
A Finger of Fudge is Just Enough

description: First ascent by Adrian Bough, H01. Set after speeding back from Fontainebleau to Iffley in 9 1/2 hours, thus taking two of the world's premier bouldering venues in one day! 41A is undercut only.

index: Hop, Skip, Jump, Leap, Fly, Die

description: A brilliant power-problem up the left hand arête, set by Geoff Hannis in M05 and finally climbed by Pete Cawley in 2012. Following a delicate sit start, power up the arête and somehow reach right for the slot (terms such as "dynamic hand jams" have been banded about here...) Step up onto 15 and then glide effortlessly (easier said than done) to the final hold... or dream on.
First ascent by Mike Pearson, M14. Difficult, strenuous climbing that became something of an infamous impossibility amongst the Iffley elite…

First ascent by Steve Broadbent, M07. The horizontal dyno is a long way for all but the tallest of climbers, and requires exceptionally precise climbing but no chips. It's short and safe, but technically as hard as they come. Welcome to the realm of weirdness...
